About the problem: Find the center and radius of a circle given its equation in standard form. Graphing tool provided to help with visualizing the geometry of the problem.
The worked example can be removed by commenting out the <hint> portion of the document.
*************************************************************-->
<problem>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="h" from="-4" to="4" exclude="0"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="-4" to="4" exclude="0"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="r" from="2" to="6"/>
  <math name="center">($h, $k)</math>
  <math name="p" simplify>($h, $k + $r)</math>
  <math name="y" simplify>$k + $r</math>
</setup>


<!--testing-->
<!-- <p>h = $h</p>
<p>r = $r</p>
<p>k = $k</p> -->
<!--testing-->

<p>A circle is described by the equation
  <me>(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2</me>
where the center of the circle is at <m>C = (h, k)</m> and <m>r</m> is its radius. </p>
<p>Given that a circle has center <m>C = $center</m>, and its circumference passes through the point <m>P = $p</m>, find the following:
  
  <ul>
    <li>the radius</li>
    <li>two other points on the circumference of the circle</li>
  </ul>
</p>


<!--*********************************************
            Graphing Tool
**********************************************-->

<aside><title>Graphing tool</title>
<p>Place the center of the circle, and drag to the correct location: <nbsp/><nbsp/> 
  <updateValue target="cP.hide" newValue="false" type="boolean">
    <label>Place center</label>
  </updateValue>
</p>
<p>Place the given point, and drag to the correct location: <nbsp/><nbsp/> 
  <updateValue target="gP.hide" newValue="false" type="boolean">
    <label>Place point</label>
  </updateValue>
</p>

  
<graph name="g1" grid="1 1"> 
  <point name="cP" hide styleNumber="8">(1, 1)
    <constraints><constrainToGrid/></constraints>
  </point>
  <point name="gP" hide styleNumber="11">(3, 1)
    <constraints><constrainToGrid/></constraints>
  </point>
  <circle name="gCirc" hide="$gP.hide = true" styleNumber="11" center="$cP" through="$gP"/>
</graph>
<p>If you found your solution geometrically, don't forget to check your answer by substituting your solution values back into the original equation!</p>
</aside>  

<!--*********************************************
            User solution input
**********************************************-->


<p><m>\text{radius} = </m> 
  <answer name="ans1a">$r</answer>
</p>

  
<p><m>P_2 = \bigg(</m> <mathInput name="p2x"/> , <mathInput name="p2y"/> <m>\bigg)</m></p>

  
<p><m>P_3 = \bigg(</m> <mathInput name="p3x"/> , <mathInput name="p3y"/> <m>\bigg)</m></p>

<setup>
  <boolean name="p2Oncircle">($p2x - $h)^2 + ($p2y - $k)^2 = $r^2</boolean>
  <boolean name="p3Oncircle">($p3x - $h)^2 + ($p3y - $k)^2 = $r^2</boolean>
  <math name="p2">($p2x, $p2y)</math>
  <math name="p3">($p3x, $p3y)</math>
  <boolean name="p2p3unique">$p2 != $p and $p3 != $p and $p2 != $p3</boolean>
  <boolean name="usedGivenPt">$p2 = $p or $p3 = $p</boolean>
</setup>

<p><answer name="ans1b">
  <award><when>$p2Oncircle and $p3Oncircle and $p2p3unique</when></award>
</answer></p>


