<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<ul>
  <li><p>Substitute the coordinates for the center of the circle in for <m>h</m> and <m>k</m> in the given equation, and the coordinates for the point on the circumference of the circle for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
  <me>($h - ($h))^2 + ($y - ($k))^2 = r^2</me></p>    
  </li>
  <li><p>Simplifying the left-hand side of this equation gives
    <me><math simplify>$r^2</math> = r^2</me>
  We take the positive square root to solve for <m>r</m>, 
    <me>r = $r</me></p>
  </li>
  <li><p>There are an infinite number of correct answers to the second part of this problem! To determine two additional points on the circle, consider points that are a distance of <m>r = 4</m> away from the center. It might help to make a sketch or use the graphical tool. When you find a point, you can check that the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> values work in the original equation.</p>
    <p>Three of the easiest points to find are: <math simplify>($h + $r, $k)</math>, <math simplify>($h - $r, $k)</math>, and <math simplify>($h, $k - $r)</math>.</p>
  </li>
</ul>   

</solution>
</problem>


